observations.recommendation:
We reiterate our prior-year audit recommendations that Management:

1. Direct the Municipal Accountant to submit immediately the lacking disbursement vouchers complete with relevant supporting documents to the Audit Team and henceforth observe the deadline set for the submission of disbursement vouchers and other financial reports as required under COA Circular 2002-003;

2. Direct the Municipal Treasurer to submit all the required reports on time to the Municipal Accountant, and the Municipal Accountant to submit to the Audit Team on the prescribed time for regular validation and verification;

3. Augment the workforce and personnel in the Accounting and Treasury Offices so that required reports are submitted promptly; and

4. Plan ahead the timing of physical count of all properties on date/s nearing yearend to give ample time for the reconciliation of records and avoid delay in the submission of the reports.

We recommended the Management to:

1. Submit BAC Resolution or justification as for the reason in resorting to Alternative Mode of Procurement – Small Value Procurement instead of Public/Competitive Bidding;

2. Submit to our office the lacking AIR and PAR/ARE or equivalent for the above procurement of five mobile phones;

3. Prepare PAR/ARE for the forthcoming procurement of property and equipment to establish accountability over them;

4. Prepare Delivery Report and submit the same to our office to notify the audit team of the time and date of the scheduled deliveries, and consider including in the report the following details:

a. Details/Particulars of the Item Purchased;
 b. PO Number and Date;
 c. Status of Delivery (Fully or Partially Delivered);
 d. Name of Supplier;
 e. Place of Delivery;
 f. Delivery Receipt/Official Receipt/Sales Invoice/Billing Statement Number and Date, thereof; and
 g. Time and Date of Delivery.

Finally, we recommend the management to strictly comply with the provisions of RA 9284 and its Revised IRR in all its procurement.

We recommend that management direct all concerned personnel to:

1. Liquidate the outstanding cash advances by compelling them to submit liquidation papers and refund the unused cash advance, if any;

2. Deduct and withhold the salaries of the concerned personnel who are still in service or connected to the LGU and offset their claim(s) against the LGU for those already separated from service for their unliquidated balances;

3. Exhaust all available remedies to recover the unliquidated cash advances for those no longer connected to the LGU including offsetting their claim(s) against the LGU or initiating legal action against them; and

4. Stop the practice of granting additional cash advances to those who have unliquidated balances.

We recommend that management direct all concerned personnel to:

1. Monitor closely the liquidation of outstanding cash advances, send written reminder/demand on the submission of liquidation report within the reglementary period; and

2. Stop the practice of granting additional cash advances to those who have unliquidated balances;

We recommended that Management:
1. Ensure the preparation of bank reconciliation statements at yearend and the recording of the corresponding reconciling items to arrive at adjusted Cash in Bank – LCCA balance before the submission of financial statements;
2. Require the Accountant and the Treasurer to conduct reconciliation of the GL and Cashbook balances to ensure completeness and accuracy of the recorded Cash in Bank – LCCA balance at year-end;
3. Cancel the checks that have been outstanding for over six months and revert back to cash and record the corresponding accounts payable and/or the related expenses/equity account;
4. Direct the Treasurer to send a written notice to the payees one month before the check becomes stale as required in Section 104 of the GAM for LGUs. Stale checks shall be reported and attached to the RCI prepared at the period of cancellation; and
5. Instruct the Municipal Accountant-Designate to make necessary adjusting entries for the stale checks.

We recommended that Management:
1. Require the Inventory Committee to expedite the completion of the physical count of all supplies and properties, and prepare and submit the corrected reports as required;
2. Direct the Municipal Treasurer to maintain the property and stock cards of the properties of the LGU, and conduct reconciliation of such records and the various Reports on Physical Count as against Accounting records, to determine the completeness, existence and accuracy of the subject accounts.

We recommended that Management:
1. Ensure that prospective bidders submit complete eligibility requirements and post the necessary bid security before they are marked as “passed” and declared as LCB;
2. Require strict compliance by the Bids and Awards Committee with the provisions of R.A. No. 9184 in the conduct of public bidding and awarding of contracts/ projects. BAC members, BAC secretariat and the TWG should familiarize themselves with different rules and regulations set forth by the Act;
3. Submit the lacking documentary requirements as required under pertinent provisions of the Act and its RIRR for further audit action;
4. Submit written justification for non-adherence to provisions of the Act and its RIRR.

We recommended that Management:
1. Prioritize and allocate funds for the capability building programs on GAD of all members of the GFPS and seek assistance of a gender analysis specialist/expert in the use of HGDG;
2. Work on the creation and staffing of the Municipal GAD Office, required under the GAD Code.

